<section class="section bg-cream">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="section-header centered">
            <span class="section-eyebrow">Why Drip for Almonds</span>
            <h2>What SDI Changes for Almond Growers</h2>
        </div>
        <div class="three-col-grid">
            <div class="info-card">
                <div class="info-card-icon">🌰</div>
                <h3>Hull Rot Prevention</h3>
                <p>Hull rot (Rhizopus and Botrytis) thrives when hulls are exposed to free moisture. SDI keeps the canopy completely dry, eliminating the primary infection pathway and dramatically reducing fungicide needs.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="info-card">
                <div class="info-card-icon">🧪</div>
                <h3>Fertigation at Scale</h3>
                <p>Almonds are heavy nitrogen, potassium, and boron consumers. SDI fertigation delivers nutrients in split applications that match uptake curves — reducing luxury consumption and improving NUE by 50%+.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="info-card">
                <div class="info-card-icon">💦</div>
                <h3>No Waterlogged Crowns</h3>
                <p>Microsprinklers wet the berm around the trunk and can create crown rot conditions. SDI laterals are placed away from the trunk, eliminating crown moisture and reducing Phytophthora pressure.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="info-card">
                <div class="info-card-icon">🌡️</div>
                <h3>Deficit Irrigation Precision</h3>
                <p>Regulated deficit irrigation (RDI) in almonds requires precise timing and volume control. SDI provides the control resolution needed to execute RDI protocols that improve kernel quality without yield loss.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="info-card">
                <div class="info-card-icon">🚜</div>
                <h3>Harvest-Ready Fields</h3>
                <p>Surface irrigation requires significant lead time before harvest to firm up the floor. SDI-irrigated fields can be harvested with minimal dry-down time, reducing the window for navel orangeworm activity in open hulls.</p>
            </div>
            <div class="highlight-card">
                <div class="highlight-card-icon">📊</div>
                <h3>Case Study: Kern County</h3>
                <p>A 640-acre almond operation in Kern County converted from microsprinklers to SDI and reduced water applications from 3.8 to 2.1 acre-feet/acre while increasing yield from 2,200 to 2,650 lbs/acre.</p>
                <a href="/growers-stories" class="btn-primary-sm" style="margin-top:16px;">All Case Studies →</a>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>

